Chemotherapy in advanced nonsmall cell lung cancer: indication, intensity, and 
duration.

Booton R(1), Thatcher N.

Author information:
(1)CRC Department of Medical Oncology, Christie Hospital NHS Trust, Manchester, 
United Kingdom.

Platinum-based combination and single-agent chemotherapy have become accepted as 
treatments for locally advanced and metastatic nonsmall cell lung cancer as a 
consequence of improved survival, quality of life, and symptom control compared 
with best supportive care. However, it is clear that a therapeutic plateau has 
been reached with current combinations requiring a re-evaluation of strategies 
to improve clinical outcomes. Dose intensification may offer one way in which to 
achieve better results, as may extension of the duration of treatment. The 
evidence suggests that dose intensification is a useful tool, and that its use 
in combination with markers of treatment duration and cumulative dose may help 
to maximize results from current active drug combinations.

